### The For Loop

A **for loop** repeats code a specific number of times.

---

### Syntax

```js
for (initialization; condition; increment) {
  // Code to repeat
}
```

| Part | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|---------|
| **Initialization** | Runs once at start | `let i = 0` |
| **Condition** | Checked before each iteration | `i < 5` |
| **Increment** | Runs after each iteration | `i++` |

---

### Example: Count to 5

```js
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}
// Output: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
```

### Loop Through an Array

```js
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry"];

for (let i = 0; i < fruits.length; i++) {
  console.log(fruits[i]);
}
```

---

### Variations

#### Decrementing Loop
```js
for (let i = 5; i >= 0; i--) { ... }
```

#### Skipping Steps
```js
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i += 2) { ... } // Even numbers only
```

#### Nested Loops
```js
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    console.log(i, j);
  }
}
```

---

> **Common Pitfall:** Off-by-one errors. Remember: arrays are 0-indexed, so loop from `0` to `length - 1`.

